Claims CLAIMS What is claimed is: 1. A paint brush assembly comprising: a handle with a handle first end, a handle second end opposing the handle first end, and a handle gripping surface; and a plurality of independently mobile bristles defining a bristle left end and a bristle right end, opposing the left end of the plurality of independently mobile bristles, the plurality of independently mobile bristles: each with a proximal bristle end directly coupled to the handle second end, extending from the handle second end and terminating at a distal free end, and with a bristle length separating the proximal bristle end and the distal free end; sectioned into a first plurality of bristles disposed at the bristle left end to define a longitudinal left end axis and collectively forming an edge tip defining an apex disposed at the terminal bristle left end and collectively forming an edge tip surface; and sectioned into a second plurality of bristles juxtaposed to the first plurality of bristles and extending from the first plurality of bristles in a transverse direction to the bristle right end, the edge tip surface of the first plurality of bristles spanning from the apex at a negative slope with respect to the longitudinal left end axis toward the second plurality of bristles with the bristle length of the first plurality of bristles longer than the bristle length of the second plurality of bristles. 2. The brush assembly according to claim 1, wherein: the first plurality of bristles is of a tetraocular filament. 3. The brush assembly according to claim 1, wherein: the second plurality of bristles are of a round filament with tipped ends. 4. The brush assembly according to claim 1, wherein the plurality of independently mobile bristles further comprise: a third plurality of bristles surrounded by the first plurality of bristles and the second plurality of bristles. 5. The brush assembly according to claim 4, wherein: the third plurality of bristles are of a quad filament. 6. The brush assembly according to claim 5, wherein: the first plurality of bristles is more stiff than the second and third plurality of bristles. 7. The brush assembly according to claim 6, wherein: the first plurality of bristles disposed at the bristle left end form an arcuate upper surface that includes the apex. 8. The brush assembly according to claim 1, wherein: the negative slope is linear and oriented at an angle of approximately 49 degrees with respect to the longitudinal left end axis. 9. The brush assembly according to claim 1, wherein: 

 at least one of the first, second, and third plurality of bristles are defined by an elongated cavity extending from the proximal bristle end to the distal free end. 10. The brush assembly according to claim 9, further comprising: a reservoir disposed in the handle second end, the reservoir being in communication with the elongated cavity of the bristles. 11. The brush assembly according to claim 1, further comprising: a ferrule encapsulating at least a portion of the handle second end and the proximal bristle end. 12. The brush assembly according to claim 1, wherein: the second plurality of bristles are disposed at an angle relative to a horizontal axis. 13. In combination with a paint brush having a handle with an end having a plurality of independently mobile bristles each extending therefrom and terminating at a distal free end, the improvement comprising: a sleeve body having: a sleeve first end defining and enclosing a first aperture with at least one of the handle and the plurality of independently mobile bristles of the brush disposed therein; a sleeve second end, opposing the sleeve first end, defining and enclosing a second aperture of a tear-drop shape, the sleeve second end of the sleeve body disposed below the distal free end of the plurality of independently mobile bristles to form a bristle shape corresponding to the tear-drop shape, the sleeve second end being narrower than the sleeve first end; and 

 a sleeve channel spanning from the first aperture to the second aperture and having the plurality of independently mobile bristles disposed therein. 14. The improvement according to claim 13, further comprising: a working bristle length separating the sleeve second end of the sleeve body and the distal free end, the bristle shape uniformly spanning the working bristle length. 15. The improvement according to claim 13, wherein a perimeter of the plurality of independently mobile bristles defines a bristle area, and further comprising: a second aperture area defined by the second aperture, the second aperture area less than the bristle area. 16. The improvement according to claim 13, wherein: the sleeve body is of an elastically deformable material. 17. A paint brush assembly comprising: a handle with a handle first end, a handle second end opposing the handle first end, and a handle gripping surface; and a plurality of independently mobile bristles defining a bristle left end and a bristle right end, opposing the left end of the plurality of independently mobile bristles, the plurality of independently mobile bristles: each with a proximal bristle end directly coupled to the handle second end, extending from the handle second end and terminating at a distal free end, and with a bristle length separating the proximal bristle end and the distal free end; 

 sectioned into a first plurality of bristles disposed at the bristle left end to define a longitudinal left end axis and collectively forming an edge tip defining an apex disposed at the terminal bristle left end and collectively forming an edge tip surface, the first plurality of bristles form an arcuate upper surface that includes the apex; sectioned into a second plurality of bristles juxtaposed to the first plurality of bristles and extending from the first plurality of bristles in a transverse direction to the bristle right end, the second plurality of bristles are disposed at an angle relative to a horizontal axis, the edge tip surface of the first plurality of bristles spanning from the apex at a negative slope with respect to the longitudinal left end axis toward the second plurality of bristles with the bristle length of the first plurality of bristles longer than the bristle length of the second plurality of bristles, the negative slope being linear and oriented at an angle of approximately 49 degrees with respect to the longitudinal left end axis; a third plurality of bristles surrounded by the first plurality of bristles and the second plurality of bristles; whereby at least one of the first, second, and third plurality of bristles are defined by an elongated cavity extending from the proximal bristle end to the distal free end; a reservoir disposed in the handle second end, the reservoir being in communication with the elongated cavity of the bristles; a sleeve body having: a sleeve first end defining and enclosing a first aperture with at least one of the handle and the plurality of independently mobile bristles disposed therein; a sleeve second end, opposing the sleeve first end, defining and enclosing a second aperture of a tear-drop shape, the sleeve second end of the sleeve body disposed below the distal free end of the plurality of independently mobile bristles to form a bristle shape corresponding to the tear-drop shape, the sleeve second end being narrower than the sleeve first end; 

 a sleeve channel spanning from the first aperture to the second aperture and having the plurality of independently mobile bristles disposed therein; and whereby a perimeter of the plurality of independently mobile bristles defines a bristle area; and whereby the sleeve second end further comprises a second aperture area defined by the second aperture, the second aperture area less than the bristle area. 18. The brush assembly according to claim 17, wherein: the first plurality of bristles is of a tetraocular filament. 19. The brush assembly according to claim 17, wherein: the second plurality of bristles are of a round filament with tipped ends. 20. The brush assembly according to claim 17, wherein: the third plurality of bristles are of a quad filament
